# Consistent Return Contracts

Methods must honor their declared return type contracts. Callers rely on consistent behavior to handle responses and errors correctly.

## Default Behavior

### Async Methods Must Not Throw Synchronously

Methods returning `Observable<T>` or `Promise<T>` must channel all errors through their async error path.

```typescript
// ✅ Default: Use throwError for Observable-returning methods
getById(id: string): Observable<User> {
  if (!id) {
    return throwError(() => new Error('ID is required'));
  }
  return this.http.get<User>(`/api/users/${id}`);
}

// ✅ Default: Use Promise.reject for Promise-returning methods
async getById(id: string): Promise<User> {
  if (!id) {
    return Promise.reject(new Error('ID is required'));
  }
  return this.fetchUser(id);
}
```

### Consistent Return Shapes

Methods should return consistent shapes - don't mix `T | undefined` with `T | null` across similar methods.

```typescript
// ✅ Consistent: All methods return null for "not found"
interface UserService {
  getById(id: string): Observable<User | null>;
  getByEmail(email: string): Observable<User | null>;
}

// ❌ Inconsistent: Mixed undefined and null
interface UserService {
  getById(id: string): Observable<User | undefined>;
  getByEmail(email: string): Observable<User | null>;
}
```

## Rationale

1. **Predictable error handling** - Callers expect to handle async errors in `.subscribe({ error })` or `.catch()`, not in try/catch around the call.
2. **Composability** - Observables that throw synchronously break RxJS pipe chains.
3. **Testability** - Consistent contracts make mocking straightforward.

## Documented Exceptions

### 1. Fail-Fast Constructor/Initialization Errors

Services that cannot function without required configuration should throw synchronously during construction.

```typescript
// ✅ Exception: Constructor validation
@Injectable({ providedIn: 'root' })
export class ApiService {
  constructor() {
    const baseUrl = inject(API_BASE_URL, { optional: true });
    if (!baseUrl) {
      throw new Error('API_BASE_URL token must be provided');
    }
  }
}
```

**Rationale:** The application should fail fast at startup rather than at runtime when the service is first used.

### 2. Developer-Facing Assertion Errors

Errors that indicate programming mistakes (not runtime conditions) may throw synchronously when they represent invariant violations.

```typescript
// ✅ Exception: Invariant violation (developer error)
updateItem(id: string, changes: Partial<Item>): Observable<Item> {
  if (Object.keys(changes).length === 0) {
    throw new Error('updateItem called with empty changes - this is a bug');
  }
  return this.http.patch<Item>(`/api/items/${id}`, changes);
}
```

**Rationale:** These errors should never occur in production; they signal bugs to fix during development.

## Anti-Patterns

```typescript
// ❌ Synchronous throw in Observable method
update(id: string, data: UpdateDto): Observable<Entity> {
  const index = this.items.findIndex(i => i.id === id);
  if (index === -1) {
    throw new Error('Entity not found');  // Breaks Observable contract
  }
  return of(this.items[index]);
}

// ❌ Mixing return contracts in same service
getUser(id: string): Observable<User | null> { }      // Returns null
getProduct(id: string): Observable<Product | undefined> { } // Returns undefined

// ❌ Returning different types based on condition
getData(): Observable<Data[] | null> {
  if (this.cache) {
    return of(this.cache);  // Returns Data[]
  }
  return of(null);  // Returns null - callers must handle both
}
```

## Validation Pattern

When you need input validation in async methods:

```typescript
// ✅ Validate and return error through Observable
create(data: CreateDto): Observable<Entity> {
  const validationError = this.validate(data);
  if (validationError) {
    return throwError(() => new ValidationError(validationError));
  }
  return this.http.post<Entity>('/api/entities', data);
}
```
